TITLE: Creating a Service Alias via Configuration Files
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to define a service alias (`app.mailer`) that points to another service definition (`App\Mail\PhpMailer`) using YAML, XML, or PHP configuration. This allows accessing the original service (which is marked private in this example) using the alias. The alias itself can be marked public.
SOURCE: https://github.com/symfony/symfony-docs/blob/7.3/service_container/alias_private.rst#2025-04-22_snippet_5

LANGUAGE: yaml
CODE:
```
# config/services.yaml
services:
    # ...
    App\Mail\PhpMailer:
        public: false

    app.mailer:
        alias: App\Mail\PhpMailer
        public: true
```

LANGUAGE: xml
CODE:
```
<!-- config/services.xml -->
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>
<container xmlns="http://symfony.com/schema/dic/services"
    xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
    xsi:schemaLocation="http://symfony.com/schema/dic/services
        https://symfony.com/schema/dic/services/services-1.0.xsd">

    <services>
        <service id="App\Mail\PhpMailer" public="false"/>

        <service id="app.mailer" alias="App\Mail\PhpMailer"/>
    </services>
</container>
```

LANGUAGE: php
CODE:
```
// config/services.php
namespace Symfony\Component\DependencyInjection\Loader\Configurator;

use App\Mail\PhpMailer;

return function(ContainerConfigurator $container): void {
    $services = $container->services();

    $services->set(PhpMailer::class)
        ->private();

    $services->alias('app.mailer', PhpMailer::class);
};
```

